messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

- Full HTTP request path:
  /printshops/{printShopID}/employees

- Are all HTTP methods acceptable (override)? 
  No

- Per-method acceptance (based on the source code annotations, not runtime behavior):
  - HEAD: No
  - POST: Yes
  - OPTIONS: No
  - TRACE: No
  - GET: Yes
  - PUT: Yes
  - DELETE: No
  - PATCH: No

Explanation:
- The ManagerController class has no class-level @RequestMapping, so the method-level mappings are full paths as written.
- The getEmployees method is annotated with @RequestMapping(value = "/printshops/{printShopID}/employees", method = RequestMethod.GET), so GET is supported for that path.
- The same path (/printshops/{printShopID}/employees) is also used by two other methods in this class:
  - addEmployee annotated with method = RequestMethod.POST — therefore POST is supported for that path.
  - editEmployee annotated with method = RequestMethod.PUT — therefore PUT is supported for that path.
- There are no mappings in this class for HEAD, OPTIONS, TRACE, DELETE, or PATCH on the path /printshops/{printShopID}/employees. (There is a DELETE mapping, but it is for the different path /printshops/{printShopID}/employees/{employeeID}.)  
- The answers above follow only the explicit @RequestMapping(method=...) annotations present in the source, per your instruction to base decisions on the code rather than runtime framework behavior.
